  Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Meriet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Merritt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Merritt","meanings":["English: variant of   Merriott  ,   Marriott  , or <b>Marritt</b>. The last of these is most often a variant of   Merriott   or   Marriott  , but possibly in some instances from Middle English <i>Marret</i> or <i>Merret</i>, a syncopated form of <i>Margaret</i>, <i>Mergeret</i>."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas de Meriet was born in 1210, in Merriott, Somerset, England, his father, Hugh de Meriet, was 26 and his mother, Isabel Fitz Payne, was 22. He married Elizabeth Rowe in August 1235, in Merriott, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1258, in England, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1210–1258":"1210–1258","1214–1267":"1214–1267","1242–1284":"1242–1284","1242–1285":"1242–1285","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1185–1236":"1185–1236","1188–1246":"1188–1246","8 April 1236":"8. aprill 1236","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1185":"1185","1284":"1284","Abt. 12 Jul 1242":"umbes 12. juuli 1242","1248":"1248","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1236":"1236","1214":"1214","Est 1235":"august 1235","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1267":"1267","1210":"1210","31 May 1246":"31. mai 1246","1188":"1188","Abt 12 July 1242":"umbes 12. juuli 1242","Merriott, Chard, Somerset, England":"Merriott, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Merriott, Somerset, England":"Merriott, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1210–1258":"1210–1258","1214–1267":"1214–1267","1242–1284":"1242–1284","1242–1285":"1242–1285","1248–Male":"1248–Kuollut","1185–1236":"1185–1236","1188–1246":"1188–1246","8 April 1236":"8. huhtikuuta 1236","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1185"